==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/seʤ/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*segja-'', from Indo-European ''*sokʷ(h)-'' ‘companion’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[sia|siā]], Old Saxon [[segg]], Old Norse [[seggr]] (Norwegian [[segg]]).  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[socius]].

====Noun====
'''secg''' ''m'' (plural '''[[secgas]]''')
# ''(poetic)'' [[man]], [[warrior]], [[hero]]

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic, from Indo-European ''*sek-'' ‘cut’.

====Noun====
'''secg''' ''f'' (plural '''[[secga]]''' or '''[[secge]]''')
# ''(poetic)'' [[sword]]

===Etymology 3===
From Germanic ''*sagjaz'', from Indo-European ''*sak-'' ‘marsh plant’ (probably related to Etymology 2).  Cognate with Middle Low German [[segge]], Russian [[осока]].

====Noun====
'''secg''' ''m''
# [[sedge]]

